description:
An Anarchist Guide to “Community Emergency Response.” Hosted by the Bay Anarchist Free School

Are we prepared for a natural disaster? In this session, we will
present and analyze the state’s plans for disaster response at the local
and federal level. We will discuss possible engagement and intervention
into the official disaster response and propose strategies for creating
an anarchist emergency response plan. Participants will leave with a
physical guide including information on conducting search and rescue,
utility shut off operations, and distributing resources.

description:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/james-spooner-special-musical-guests-tickets-638806416187?aff=erelexpmlt

The Berkeley Public Library presents award-winning graphic novelist and filmmaker, James Spooner, in conversation at Berkeley’s iconic 924 Gilman Street (Alternative Music Foundation). He will discuss his 2022 graphic novel, The High Desert: Black. Punk. Nowhere., a formative coming-of-age graphic memoir. The High Desert depicts Spooner’s reckoning with identity, racism, clumsy teen love and belonging in an isolated California desert town while searching for salvation and community through punk.

Joining James Spooner in conversation is Justin Hall, award-winning cartoonist, scholar, and educator who is based in the Bay Area.

This author talk will conclude with a live musical performance by special, punk music guests. The artist will be announced as we get closer to the event.

James will be bringing copies of The High Desert: Black. Punk. Nowhere., for sale and signing at this event.

description:
The grass pink or wild ground phlox is one of the earliest widespread flowers of the spring.  Other names were the Full Sprouting Grass Moon, the Egg Moon, and  — among coastal tribes  — the Full Fish Moon, when the shad came upstream to spawn. This is also the first full moon of spring  —  the so-called Paschal Moon. Ecclesiastical rules mandate that the first Sunday after this moon is Easter, and so it will be on the 9th.
